    fullStory: `After the Fall of mankind in the Garden of Eden, sin spread rapidly across the earth. What began as one act of disobedience by Adam and Eve multiplied in every generation. People no longer lived in harmony with God. Instead, they chose their own ways, living selfishly, hurting one another, and turning away from the Creator. The world became filled with wickedness, and the King of heaven saw that the hearts of men were continually evil.

As the corruption of humanity spread, God decided to bring judgment upon the earth. The King of heaven would send a great flood to cleanse the world of its sin. But because Noah had been faithful, God decided to save him and his family. He commanded Noah to build a massive ark, a great ship, to protect them from the coming flood. The ark had to be built with gopher wood, sealed with pitch, and large enough to hold Noah's family and two of every kind of animal—male and female—so that life could continue after the flood.

Noah obeyed without question. For years, he worked on the ark while others mocked and laughed at him. But Noah's trust in the King was unshaken. He believed in God's promise, even when others rejected it. He built the ark just as God had instructed him, showing his deep faith in the God who ruled over all creation.

When the ark was finished, God told Noah to gather his family and the animals. The animals came to Noah, two by two, just as God had commanded. Once they were all safely inside, God shut the door of the ark. And then the rains began.

For forty days, the earth was covered with water. The flood was a judgment on the wickedness that had taken over the earth. But in the ark, Noah and his family were safe. God, the true King, had not abandoned them. He kept His promise and protected them from the destruction around them.

After the rain stopped, Noah waited. The floodwaters receded slowly, and Noah sent out a raven to see if the waters had gone down. Then he sent out a dove, and the dove returned with a freshly plucked olive leaf. Noah knew that the earth was drying, and soon it would be time to leave the ark.

Finally, when the ground was dry, God told Noah to leave the ark. As Noah and his family stepped out onto the dry land, God made a promise. "Never again will I destroy the earth with a flood," God said. To remind Noah and all future generations of His promise, God placed a rainbow in the sky. The rainbow became a symbol of God's covenant with His people, a reminder of His faithfulness and His rule over the earth.

Noah's story is a powerful reminder that God is the King who rules over all. Even when sin and rebellion were widespread, God remained faithful. Though He judged the earth, He also kept His promises and showed mercy. The rainbow reminds us of God's eternal promise to His people and His commitment to His covenant.`,
